# Access Control

## Roles

- **Admin** — the person who installs company-brain (see `project_install.md`).
  Has access to all company accounts/providers, owns configuration, and scopes
  every member's access. Onboarding is performed by the admin.
- **Member** (employee) — may connect their own accounts. The admin scopes what
  each member can do, along two independent axes (below).

## Two scopes per member (admin-controlled)

1. **Ingest scope** — which of the member's platform accounts (and which
   platforms) are ingested into the wiki Markdown. Only admin-approved sources
   feed the wiki.
2. **Read scope** — which wiki areas (sections/pages) the member may read back.
   Independent of ingest scope: a member may contribute data they cannot broadly
   read.

## Read access: humans vs member AI agents

**Humans (members)** read through **Notion teamspaces**. Notion enforces who sees
what; the admin sets each teamspace's access level. company-brain routes each wiki
area to the right teamspace via `config/notion.yaml`.

**Member AI agents** (Cursor, Claude Desktop, other MCP clients) do **not** get
direct access to the Markdown wiki volume, filesystem paths, or admin CLI on the
wiki host. They converse with company-brain only through the **member bridge MCP**
(HTTP, private mesh). The bridge is a safety layer: fixed tools, schema-validated
writes, prefix-scoped reads, per-member bearer tokens. See **Member bridge MCP**
below.

The full Markdown wiki (source of truth) remains **admin-only** for humans and for
admin tooling (`company-brain` CLI on the wiki host). Members never receive
`COMPANY_BRAIN_WIKI_DIR`, wiki checkout, or a token that can read arbitrary paths.

- `config/notion.yaml` `teamspaces`: teamspace key -> the Notion parent page that
  pages in that teamspace sync under.
- `config/notion.yaml` `section_teamspace`: wiki section (exact or path prefix)
  -> a teamspace key, or `admin_only` to keep that section **MD-only** (never
  mirrored to Notion). `NotionSync` routes/skips accordingly.
- **Default install:** two teamspaces — `admin` (finance, legal, admin) and
  `company` (engineering, product, growth). Optional engineering / product /
  growth parents may be set later; empty split keys fall back to `company`
  (`resolve_teamspace_parent`). Admin-only sections stay MD-only or admin teamspace.

## Employee wikis (per-member buildings)

Each member has an `employee_wiki/{member}/` building alongside the company wiki.
The same MD-first / Notion-mirror posture applies, with a per-page label instead
of section routing:

- **Page-level `sync:` frontmatter** (resolved by `notion/sync_routing.py`):
  `private` (member's personal teamspace `member_{key}`), `company` (company
  teamspace), `admin_only` (admin teamspace), `location:{key}` (named teamspace),
  or `not_synced` (MD-only, never mirrored). Sharing is done via Notion page
  permissions on `private` pages — never an MD-side ACL.
- **`config/members.yaml`** is the member index (pointers only; secrets in `.env`):
  per-member `ingest` scope (which platforms feed the member's wiki) and
  `query_grants` (which other members may query the member's `not_synced` paths).
  These two scopes are independent and admin-controlled, mirroring the ingest vs
  read split above.
- **Imports** (zip of `.md`) are always quarantined, security-scanned, and
  duplicate-checked; the first import per member requires admin approval before
  promotion (`agents/employee_wiki/`).

## External wiki mounts (admin-only)

One-shot import of shared external Markdown wikis into `wiki/external/{source}/`.
Admin initiates only; members cannot mount external wikis.

- **Registry:** `config/external_sources.yaml` — source metadata + mount history (pointers only).
- **Pipeline:** quarantine → security scan → duplicate detection → admin review
  (`admin/mount-review/{id}.md`) → promote with provenance frontmatter.
- **Default sync:** promoted pages default to `company` teamspace (configurable per source);
  review pages and the content catalog use `admin_only` / admin teamspace.
- **Admin catalog:** `admin/content-catalog.md` lists company wiki, external mounts,
  employee building counts, and audit pages — view-only; regenerate via `company-brain catalog`.
- **Section routing:** `section_teamspace` maps top-level `admin` → admin teamspace.

## Slack interactive access (`@wiki` and `@weave`)

**`@wiki` (wiki bot):** Humans only; internal channels only. Connect channels are
ingest/read-only — no Q&A. Channel ACL in `config/slack_channels.json` maps each
enabled channel to wiki read prefixes and a Notion teamspace for citations.
`members.yaml` `role: admin` bypasses per-user rate limits. Answers cite Notion
mirror URLs, not raw MD paths.

**`@weave` (Weave bot, optional):** System-change requests only. Active W2 members
in `config/members.yaml` may invoke; `config/roster.yaml` entries **cannot**.
`config_only` changes auto-dispatch a draft PR; `agent_behavior` / `security_ingest`
require admin approval in the Notion change-request database. Weave never widens
wiki or bridge read scope.

## Member bridge MCP (planned)

Bridge process runs **co-located with the wiki** on the same host (cloud VM or
local always-on NAS/home server). Setup recommends **all-local or all-cloud**;
mixed wiki-on-NAS + agents-in-cloud is unsupported without explicit migration.

| Actor | Access |
|-------|--------|
| Admin | CLI on wiki host; full MD |
| Member (human) | Notion teamspaces |
| Member (coding agent / LLM) | Bridge MCP only — never raw MD |

**Tokens:** per-member bearer tokens; **hashes only** in gitignored
``config/bridge-tokens.json`` (plaintext shown once at issuance). Issued at
employee onboarding; revoked when a Slack offboarding agent detects member
removal. No admin god-token via MCP.

**Writes:** append-only ledger (``config/bridge_events.jsonl``) →
``bridge_manager`` → ``bridge_event_materializer`` →
``employee_wiki/{member}/blockers/``; daily 08:00 ``blocker_rollup`` compiles
company summary only (no Linear integration — issue tracking stays in Linear via
each coding agent's own integrations).

**Reads (bridge):** **department-scoped** for member AI agents. Visibility from
frontmatter ``sync:`` plus ``config/bridge.yaml`` allow-list prefixes. Maintained
**bridge index** per department (and company-wide slice), rebuilt on wiki
write/sync.

Each member token carries ``bridge.departments`` from onboarding (required for
dept access — no blanket cross-department read). A token may read:

1. **Company-wide** — ``sync: company`` under company allow-list prefixes only
   (e.g. cross-department priority master table). Not a substitute for
   department content.
2. **Department** — ``sync: location:{dept}`` when ``{dept}`` is in the member's
   ``bridge.departments``. Engineering wiki pages use ``sync: location:engineering``
   (Notion engineering teamspace). Finance → ``location:finance``, etc.
3. **Employee (own tree)** — ``employee_wiki/{member}/`` with ``sync: private``
   or ``sync: company``.

Always **deny:** other departments' ``location:*`` pages, ``sync: admin_only``,
``sync: not_synced``, other members' ``sync: private`` (unless ``query_grants``).

Human members still read their department via Notion teamspace ACL; bridge
enforces the same boundary for AI agents via ``bridge.departments``.

**Rate limits (default, admin-overridable in ``config/bridge.yaml``):** 60
reads/minute per token; 20 ``report_blocker`` calls/day per token.

**Priority master table:** lives on a ``sync: company`` wiki page (Notion-mirrored);
leads edit via Notion; rollup agent reads it at 08:00.

**Skills manifest:** per-department, e.g.
``engineering/practices/skills/_index.yaml`` (``sync: location:engineering``).

Reachability via private mesh (e.g. Tailscale). Local always-on NAS supported;
uptime/downtime tradeoffs are the admin's choice — bridge **hard fails** when
host is unreachable.

**v1 tools:** ``report_blocker``, ``get_priority``, ``search_practices``,
``get_skill``, ``list_skills``. Blockers are a **summary compilation layer** —
not linked to Linear inside 4r7a.

Skill for agent clients: ``.cursor/skills/4r7a-bridge/SKILL.md`` (first install
artifact when connecting a member's coding agent).

## Read vs write asymmetry (the default posture)

- **Reading is least-privilege**, enforced by Notion teamspace permissions; the
  admin grants access per teamspace. Sensitive sections stay `admin_only`.
- **Writing/ingesting is generally allowed** once the ingested content is
  validated — the eval/verify gate (`BaseAgent.verify`) confirms validity before
  it lands. Rationale: a bad write is recoverable, a bad read leaks information.

## Invariants

- The admin's scoping (config + Notion teamspace permissions) is the source of
  truth; agents must not widen a member's access or mirror an `admin_only`
  section to Notion.
- Finance platforms (Mercury, Ramp) stay **read-only at the source** regardless
  of role (see `agent-construction`).

